    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the leak isn't in the obvious places, you need to start looking at the *sources* of allocation across the entire codebase, not just the telemetry loop. A systematic approach is to instrument the code—like putting a small, persistent counter in every single place where `new` is called.\n\nSince you can't use heavy tools, you can use a \"printf-style\" logging mechanism that increments a global counter every time memory is requested. When the leak appears, you check the global allocation count against the global deallocation count. If they diverge, you know *something* is leaking, and you can then focus your manual review on the modules that have the highest allocation frequency.\n\nThink of it like tracking the number of hungry little goblins; if you see more goblins being spawned than being sent back to the lair, you know where the spawning mechanism is faulty. You can't catch every single one, but you can track the population trend.",
